{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17568681","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17568681"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:20:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:20:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21298"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"21298","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/21298"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.75,0.05,0.14,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"14171"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102108"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"14171","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/14171"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21298"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84558"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"1804"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"10964"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"34369"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34873"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35569"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35570"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35571"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102108","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102108"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 85-year-old Indigenous woman presents to the Emergency Department of a rural hospital with three days of progressive shortness of breath on a background of two months of fatigue. She has a medical history of diabetes mellitus, hypertension, and childhood acute rheumatic fever. She takes metformin and perindopril regularly. She does not smoke or drink alcohol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 92/min, blood pressure 138/78 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 94% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. There is an apical pan-systolic murmur on auscultation, which is unchanged from previous examination in hospital. There are crepitations at both lung bases and her hands are cool to touch. No peripheral oedema is noted.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acute myocardial infarction","Congestive cardiac failure","Pulmonary embolism","Anaemia of chronic disease","Community-acquired pneumonia"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECongestive cardiac failure\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely diagnosis in this scenario. The patient presents with progressive shortness of breath, basal crepitations, and cold peripheries, all of which are classic features of heart failure. Her history of hypertension and diabetes mellitus are significant risk factors, and previous acute rheumatic fever may have contributed to valvular dysfunction, further increasing her risk. The chronicity of her symptoms (fatigue over two months) and the absence of fever or chest pain support this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute myocardial infarction\u003C/strong\u003E can precipitate heart failure. However, patients typically present with acute chest pain, diaphoresis, and sometimes shortness of breath. It is important to note that atypical presentations (e.g., silent myocardial ischaemia) may be seen in people with diabetes. Nevertheless, the gradual progression of symptoms makes this less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPulmonary embolism\u003C/strong\u003E can present with acute shortness of breath and tachypnoea, but typically has a more sudden onset and is often associated with pleuritic chest pain, haemoptysis, or risk factors for thromboembolism. The gradual progression of symptoms and the presence of bilateral crepitations make this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnaemia of chronic disease\u003C/strong\u003E can cause fatigue and sometimes shortness of breath, but it would not explain the presence of basal crepitations or cold peripheries. There is no mention of pallor or laboratory findings to support this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommunity-acquired pneumonia\u003C/strong\u003E may present with shortness of breath and crepitations, but the absence of fever, cough, or focal chest findings makes this less likely. The chronicity of her symptoms and the presence of risk factors for heart failure further support a cardiac cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s worth noting that rheumatic heart disease (RHD) is a possible underlying contributor to this patient\u0027s heart failure, given her childhood history of acute rheumatic fever and the presence of an apical pan-systolic murmur. RHD commonly affects the mitral valve, causing regurgitation or stenosis, which can lead to heart failure. In this case, the clinical syndrome described is that of heart failure, likely with RHD as a contributing cause, along with hypertension and diabetes being ischemic heart disease risk factors.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Congestive cardiac failure commonly presents with progressive dyspnoea, basal crepitations, and peripheral hypoperfusion, especially in older adults with risk factors.","A history of hypertension and diabetes mellitus increases the risk of developing heart failure.","Previous acute rheumatic fever increases the risk of valvular heart disease, which can contribute to heart failure in later life."],"references":["The 2020 Australian guideline for prevention, diagnosis and management of acute rheumatic fever and rheumatic heart disease. Menzies School of Health Research. Updated March 2022. Available from: https://www.rhdaustralia.org.au/system/files/fileuploads/arf_rhd_guidelines_3.2_edition_march_2022.pdf","Kumar RK, Antunes MJ, Beaton A, et al. Contemporary Diagnosis and Management of Rheumatic Heart Disease: Implications for Closing the Gap: A Scientific Statement From the American Heart Association [published correction appears in Circulation. 2021 Jun 8;143(23):e1025-e1026. doi: 10.1161/CIR.0000000000000984.]. Circulation. 2020;142(20):e337-e357. doi:10.1161/CIR.0000000000000921"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84558"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21298"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84558","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84558"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-07T19:34:57+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-07T19:35:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"14171"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102108"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":